-- South African Stocks Rise For Second Day in Three, Led by Anglo, SABMiller
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-24T16:36:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-24/south-african-stocks-fall-led-down-by-capital-shopping-eastern-platinum.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for the second day in three, adding 217.42, or
0.7 percent, to 31,112.49 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, snapped three days of losses, gaining 4.95 rand, or 1.6
percent, to 323.95 rand. Anglo could sell some of its assets in
South Africa to improve its own valuation, Liberum Capital Ltd.
analysts led by  Michael Rawlinson  said in a note yesterday.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd . (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest producer
of the metal, fell for the first day in three, losing 4.36 rand,
or 1.3 percent, to 332.49 rand. Gold fell for the first time in
three sessions in New York on speculation that the biggest rally
in two weeks was overdone.  Capital Shopping Centres Group Plc , (CSO SJ), the U.K.’s
largest shopping mall owner, slipped for a second day, dropping
1.32 cents, or 3.3 percent, to 39.08 rand, the lowest level
since Sept. 7. Capital Shopping confirmed to shareholders that
it was in advanced discussions to acquire 100 percent of
Trafford Centre for 750 million pounds ($1.2 billion) from Peel
Group.  Eastern Platinum Ltd.  (EPS SJ), a producer of the precious
metal in South Africa, retreated for the third day in four,
losing 81 cents, or 6.7 percent, to 11.21 rand, the lowest since
Oct. 28. Eastern Platinum said it will sell 196 million shares
to raise C$302.2 million ($296 million) to fund the first phase
of its Eastern Limb development and working capital.  Jasco Electronics Holdings Ltd.  (JSC SJ), a
telecommunications operator, increased the most since Oct. 11,
adding 8 cents, or 6.4 percent, to 1.33 rand. Shareholders today
approved Jasco’s proposed acquisition of  Spescom Ltd. , the
company said in a statement.  IPSA Group Plc  (IPS SJ), a London-based builder of power
stations in southern Africa, surged 25 cents, or 22 percent, to
1.40 rand, the highest since Oct. 25. Eskom Holdings Ltd., South
Africa’s state-owned power utility, said it has budgeted 12
billion rand ($1.7 billion) to purchase power from independent
producers over the next three years, according to Business
Report newspaper.  Pioneer Foods Ltd.  (PFG SJ), a diversified food producer,
climbed for the second time in three days, adding 1.15 cents, or
2.4 percent, to 49.40 rand. The Competition Tribunal today
adjourned a hearing into Pioneer’s 1.05 billion-rand settlement
agreement with the Competition Commission to Nov. 30.  SABMiller Plc  (SAB SJ), the world’s second-largest brewer
by volume, advanced 1.23 rand, or 0.5 percent, to 233.53 rand.
The brewer said it has entered the Argentinian market through
the acquisition of Cerveceria Argentina S.A. Isenbeck, that
country’s third-largest brewing company.  Santova Logistics Ltd.  (SNV SJ), a clearing agent for
importers and exporters, declined 1 cent, or 11 percent, to 8
cents, the lowest since Nov. 19. The company said fiscal first-
half net income rose to 9.3 million rand from 463,000 rand a
year earlier.  Simeka Business Group Ltd.  (SBG SJ), a computer-hardware
and support company, declined for the second day in three,
losing 1 cent, or 7.7 percent, to 12 cents. In a modified annual
financial statement today, Simeka said its loss for the year
through May was 251 million rand, and not the 242 million rand
announced in August.  To contact the reporter on this story:
